{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517530"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.07,0.74,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44435"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents with a 3-month history of chest pain and shortness of breath when exercising lifting weights or running on a treadmill. His history includes hypertension and gallstones. He is compliant with the verapamil for his blood pressure control. He is a non-smoker and drinks about four glasses of wine at weekends. His BMI is 26. On examination his blood pressure is 165/55 mmHg, pulse 85/min, temperature = 37.3 \u00b0C and respiratory rate 17/min. There is a 4/6 crescendo-decrescendo murmur heard at the right upper sternal border with radiation to the carotid arteries, weak and delayed carotid pulses, and an S4 gallop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG reveals sinus rhythm without arrhythmia. On echocardiography he has an ejection fraction (EF) of 45% and an aortic valve area of 0.8 cm\u00b2 (normal 3.0-4.0). One year ago he had a coronary angiogram which showed a 20% lesion in the mid-left anterior descending (LAD) artery, a 30% lesion in the right coronary artery (RCA) and no significant stenosis in the left circumflex artery (LCx).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation with regular follow-up","Lifestyle modifications and exercise counseling","Carotid doppler ultrasound","Transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR)","Coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms, physical examination findings (including the crescendo-decrescendo murmur, weak and delayed carotid pulses), and echocardiogram results (EF 45% and aortic valve area 0.8 cm\u00b2) suggest significant aortic valve stenosis. Aortic valve stenosis can cause chest pain, dyspnoea on exertion, and reduced exercise tolerance. In severe cases, it can lead to heart failure. The presence of a 4/6 crescendo-decrescendo murmur with radiation to the carotid arteries, weak and delayed carotid pulses, and an S4 gallop indicates severe aortic stenosis with associated left ventricular hypertrophy and impaired left ventricular function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation with regular follow-up \u003C/strong\u003Emay be an appropriate strategy for asymptomatic patients with less severe aortic stenosis. However, in this case, the patient is experiencing symptoms (chest pain and dyspnoea) and has severe aortic stenosis, indicating the need for intervention rather than observation alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Elifestyle modifications and exercise counselling \u003C/strong\u003Eplay an essential role in managing cardiovascular health, they are not the primary management strategy for severe aortic stenosis. These measures may include encouraging regular physical activity, maintaining a healthy diet, controlling hypertension, and managing other cardiovascular risk factors. The clinical scenario in this case suggests that the patient does exercise appropriately and has a reasonable body weight. However, his severe aortic stenosis requires a more definitive intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E will assess for carotid stenosis; however, the murmur heard in the neck is referred from the aortic valve. Carotid doppler is not the primary intervention for severe aortic stenosis. It may be indicated if there is suspicion of carotid artery disease or if the patient has symptoms of transient ischemic attacks or strokes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscatheter aortic valve replacement\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive procedure where a diseased aortic valve is replaced with a prosthetic valve. In this case, the patient has severe aortic stenosis, as evidenced by the symptoms of chest pain and dyspnoea on exertion, the physical examination findings (murmur, weak and delayed carotid pulses), and the echocardiogram results (EF of 45% and aortic valve area of 0.8 cm\u00b2). TAVR is the preferred treatment for severe symptomatic aortic stenosis, especially in patients who are at intermediate to high surgical risk or considered inoperable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary artery bypass grafting \u003C/strong\u003Eis a surgical procedure performed to bypass significant coronary artery stenosis and improve blood flow to the heart muscle. In this case, the prior coronary angiography showed mild stenosis in the LAD and RCA without significant stenosis in the LCx. These findings suggest that the patient\u0027s symptoms and physical examination findings are primarily due to severe aortic stenosis rather than coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aortic valve replacement (AVR) is superior to medical therapy in severe symptomatic aortic stenosis."],"references":["Boskovski MT, Gleason TG. Current Therapeutic Options in Aortic Stenosis. Circ Res. 2021; 128:1398-1417. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33914604/","Gheorghe GS, Hodorogea AS, Gheorghe ACD, Nanea IT, Ciobanu A. Medical management of symptomatic severe aortic stenosis in patients non-eligible for transcatheter aortic valve implantation. J Geriatr Cardiol. 2020 Nov 28;17(11):704-709. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7729185/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44435"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44435"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T13:43:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T13:43:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5252"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[